- Thu 13 Jun 2019. Situation report 2, Uganda Ministry of Health
[WHO Africa, abridged, edited]
https://www.afro.who.int/sites/default/files/2019-06/Ebola%20Virus%20Disease%20Sitrep%202%2013th%20June%202019.pdf


On 11 Jun 2019, the Ministry of Health of Uganda declared the 6th outbreak of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in the country affecting Kasese district in South Western Uganda. The 1st case was a 5-year-old child with a recent history of travel to the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC). This child was one of 6 people that escaped from the DRC while still being monitored as suspect cases following a burial of the grandfather who succumbed to EVD. The child was ill by the time he crossed into Uganda and the mother took him for medical care at Kagando hospital in Kasese district with symptoms of vomiting blood, bloody diarrhea, muscle pain, headache, fatigue, and abdominal pain. The child tested positive for Ebola Zaire by PCR and he later died on [11 Jun 2019]. 2 other members of the family, a grandmother and 3-year-old brother also tested positive for Ebola on 12 Jun 2019 and died later the same day [12 Jun 2019]. Today, the 3-year-old confirmed case and his mother (asymptomatic) were returned to the DRC for further management together with 3 other family members including the father, house help, and an 8-month-old brother. As of today, there is no confirmed case in Uganda, however 4 suspected cases have been admitted at Bwera Ebola treatment unit. 98 contacts have been line listed for follow up so far.

--
