- Thu 13 Jun 2019. Three suspected Ebola victims escape from Kanungu (Uganda) isolation
[Daily Monitor, abridged, edited]
https://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Three-suspected-Ebola-victims-escape-Kanungu-isolation-centre/688334-5155380-6atmb0/index.html


Three suspected Ebola victims have escaped from the isolation centre at Kihihi Health Centre IV in Kihihi town council in Kanungu district in western Uganda. The 3 were admitted in isolation when they presented with Ebola like symptoms shortly after arriving at Munyaga border crossing in Western ward in Butogota town council in Kanungu district from DRC on Wednesday morning [12 Jun 2019].

The trio presented with high temperatures, one of the signs of the haemorrhagic fever forcing Ebola surveillance officials to rush them to Kihihi health centre IV for monitoring.

However, the Kanungu Health Inspector, Kato Besisira, says the trio escaped as the health workers were preparing to draw blood samples from them and rush them to Uganda Virus Research Institute (UVRI) Entebbe for examination.

They are suspected to have crossed back to DRC using the porous borders. Besisira says the escape of the trio has triggered panic in the district.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[The rapidly unfolding story of how one family brought Ebola over the border from the DRC to Uganda unfortunately exemplifies many of the contact tracing and containment issues that have confounded attempts to control the outbreak in the DRC:
- As described by WHO official Dr Mike Ryan, the index case of the family's grandfather, a Congolese pastor, became ill and died in the community, and the diagnosis of Ebola was only confirmed post-mortem. He had thus not previously encountered Ebola healthcare workers and was among the 50% or more of emerging cases that were not on known contact lists.
- More than 80 people attended this man's burial, at high risk of exposure, resulting in 27 people (presumably including the index family members) being followed by health workers.
- As described in recent ProMED posts, 12 out of 14 family members were ill and recognized as suspect Ebola cases when they reached the DRC-Uganda border at Kasindi, and were pending transfer to a DRC Ebola treatment centre, when 6 family members escaped and crossed in Uganda, reaching Kasese town before they were discovered and brought to the Byeri, Uganda Ebola unit. 2 family members died there, while the rest of the family were eventually transferred to a Congolese ETC.
- Meanwhile, as reported by the Daily Monitor, 3 non-family members entered Uganda at a different border crossing far south of Kasindi, and presumably these are the 3 suspect cases from the index case's burial mentioned in the AP report above. They were brought to the Kihihi health centre, but then they escaped. Whereabouts unknown, but presumably back to the DRC.
Evading monitoring and treatment clearly leads to additional cases in the broader community, and the question must be raised as to whether and how stronger containment methods are needed to isolate highly suspect and indeed confirmed cases of Ebola.

Selected articles in the mainstream press that have also been covering these developments may be found at the following links:
- Mail Online, 13 Jun 2109: https://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-7136397/Ebola-outbreak-kills-second-victim-Uganda-incurable-deadly-virus-spreads.html
-The New York Times, 13 Jun 2019: https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/13/world/africa/ebola-outbreak-uganda.html
- Mod.LXL]

******
[2] Outbreak summaries
- Thu 13 Jun 2019. Ebola outbreak in DRC, Uganda tops 2100 cases
[CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy), edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/06/ebola-outbreak-drc-uganda-tops-2100-cases
[Byline: Stephanie Soucheray]


The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) confirmed 21 more Ebola cases today [13 Jun 2019], which will raise the outbreak total to 2108 cases in a 10-month-long crisis that now includes 3 cases in neighboring Uganda.

Included in today's tally are 5 repatriated Congolese patients who were identified in Uganda earlier this week, when a 5-year-old boy became the 1st person in Uganda to be diagnosed as having Ebola during this outbreak. The boy died [11 Jun 2019] from the disease, as has his grandmother.

An infection in his 3-year-old brother brings the cluster to 8 cases, all of which are now classified as cases in Mabalako health zone [North Kivu] by DRC health officials.

The boy -- whose grandfather died of Ebola in Mabalako -- and several members of his family were identified at border crossings between the 2 countries and initially seen and treated in Kasese, Uganda, about 140 kilometers (85 miles) from Beni, DRC.

The DRC today [13 Jun 2019] also confirmed 6 new Ebola deaths, bringing the outbreak fatality total to 1411. Officials are tracking 335 suspected cases.

UNICEF response
---------------
Today [13 Jun 2019] UNICEF announced the launch of an emergency response plan in Uganda, which will cost USD 3.9 million and focus on communication, education, and sanitation.

"As our thoughts are with this young boy's family, this is a tragic reminder that even one case of Ebola is one too many," said UNICEF Representative in Uganda, Doreen Mulenga, MD in a press release.

"We must do everything possible to stop this outbreak in its tracks and prevent other needless deaths. UNICEF is intensifying its efforts to do so and minimize this outbreak's potentially devastating impact on children and communities at-large in Uganda."

Uganda confirms 3 cases, with 1 suspected
-----------------------------------------
According to the World Health Organization's (WHO's) Uganda office, there are 3 confirmed cases of Ebola in that country and one suspected case --involving a 23-year-old man. The confirmed cases are the index patient, his grandmother, and the boy's brother, who is being treated.

Officials are following 27 case contacts and will administer 400 donated doses of rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine in a ring vaccination effort around the case contacts. The DRC donated the vaccine to Ugandan health officials, and the ring vaccination campaign is expected to start tomorrow [14 Jun 2019].

For months, Ugandan officials have prepared for an Ebola patient crossing into the country. Throughout the week, leaders have taken to Twitter to reaffirm their country's ability to handle the outbreak.

"We appeal to the public and malicious individuals to desist from spreading false rumors about the Ebola outbreak generally and on social media," said Jane Ruth Aceng, MD, Uganda's minister of health in a statement posted to Twitter. "The outbreak is REAL and we urge all residents of Uganda to remain vigilant."

Three more health workers infected in DRC
-----------------------------------------
Today [13 Jun 2019] the DRC's health ministry confirmed that one of the new cases involves a vaccinated health worker in Mabalako.

Yesterday the ministry confirmed that 2 of 13 newly recorded cases were in unvaccinated health workers in Mabalako. One of those health workers died in in the health center where he was working, which officials consider a community death.

There are now 116 health workers infected during this outbreak, including 38 deaths.

DRC officials today said ring vaccination in their country continues, with 133 328 people so far vaccinated with Merck's unlicensed vaccine.

WHO experts to meet tomorrow
----------------------------
Tomorrow [14 Jun 2019] the WHO's Ebola emergency committee will meet to discuss the new cases in Uganda and assess if the situation now warrants a public health emergency of international concern (PHEIC) under International Health Regulations. The group declined to designate the outbreak a PHEIC in 2 previous meetings.

Also today, the European Union (EU) announced an additional funding package of Euro 3.5 million (USD 3.95 million), of which Euro 2.5 million (USD 2.82 million) is for Uganda and Euro 1 million (USD 1.13 million) for South Sudan. This is in addition to the Euro 17 million (USD19.16 million) the EU has already given to the DRC since 2018.

"Our funding is helping with surveillance, work with local communities, and boosting local capacities for these countries to take timely and effective action. We are committed to continue our assistance to bring this outbreak to an end, for as long as it takes," said Christos Stylianides, the commissioner for Humanitarian Aid and Crisis management and EU Ebola, in a press release.

--
